				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\mathscr {F}}}(x)$$\end{document}F(x) is higher than that of x, which is the second condition that the RA block needs to satisfy. ResNet2 shows that the “level” of semantics can be enriched by stacking layers (depth). However, the semantic gap does not exist for untrained models with randomly initialized parameters. Therefore, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\mathscr {F}}}$$\end{document}F should be trained preferentially compared to the RA branch. We adopt two approaches to make \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\mathscr {F}}}(x)$$\end{document}F(x) be trained preferentially. Firstly, we initialize \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\gamma$$\end{document}γ to 0, which means \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\mathscr {G}}}(X) = 1$$\end{document}G(X)=1. This setup allows the RA block to initially perform residual learning and gradually adapt during training. Furthermore, we modify Eq. (7) as follows:8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} {{\mathscr {G}}}(X) = \frac{{\gamma \cdot {{\mathscr {N}}}({{\mathscr {P}}}(X))}}{temp } + 1\in {R^C}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}G(X)=γ·N(P(X))temp+1∈RC,where temp represents temperature annealing strategy27 for facilitating the training process. The temp is not a fixed value but changes dynamically with training iterations. In this paper, we linearly reduce temp from 30 to 1 in the first 10 epochs of training. It slows down the training of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\mathscr {G}}}$$\end{document}G, widening the semantic gap between \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\mathscr {F}}}(x)$$\end{document}F(x) and x.

