The activation function Softmax almost cuts off the identity mapping in residual learning, so it degrades the model performance. Compared to the baseline, using Softmax in the reverse attention branch leads to a drop of 0.3% and 0.2% in Top-1 and Top-5 accuracy, respectively. The Sigmoid activation function brings a 0.7% improvement in Top-1 accuracy. In M-GRN, a constant term of 1 is added to ensure that the RA architecture degenerates into residual learning when \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\gamma \cdot {{\mathscr {N}}}({{\mathscr {P}}}(X))=0}$$\end{document}γ·N(P(X))=0. The experimental results in Table 8 prove its effectiveness. Without adding extra consumption, it improves both Top-1 accuracy by 1.0% compared to the baseline.

